1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,477
Part Two moves from access to reproducible analysis.

2
00:00:03,477 --> 00:00:08,259
Biomedical projects combine data, software, parameters, compute resources, and scientific interpretation.

3
00:00:08,259 --> 00:00:12,171
Reproducibility requires us to describe all of those layers.

4
00:00:12,171 --> 00:00:19,126
We will explain why environments exist, why Miniforge and Bioconda are useful, why Snakemake models dependencies,

5
00:00:19,126 --> 00:00:22,169
and how Slurm executes the expensive work.

6
00:00:22,169 --> 00:00:30,427
We will use two intentionally small examples: a statistical analysis of tabular data and a DNA sequence workflow using

7
00:00:30,427 --> 00:00:31,297
synthetic reads.

8
00:00:31,297 --> 00:00:34,774
The goal is not to teach every method.

9
00:00:34,774 --> 00:00:40,860
The goal is to establish a structure that remains understandable when a project grows.

10
00:00:40,860 --> 00:00:45,008
A scientific result depends on more than the code file.

11
00:00:45,008 --> 00:00:52,889
It also depends on input data, software versions, parameters, reference data, the order of operations, and the compute environment.

12
00:00:52,889 --> 00:01:00,770
If any of those are implicit, a colleague may be unable to reproduce the result even when the script

13
00:01:00,770 --> 00:01:01,599
is available.

14
00:01:01,599 --> 00:01:09,065
A good workflow separates immutable source data from generated output, records software dependencies, and makes each transformation explicit.

15
00:01:09,065 --> 00:01:14,458
In regulated or clinically adjacent work, this structure also supports review and provenance.

16
00:01:14,458 --> 00:01:19,850
The cluster does not automatically make work reproducible; it only provides shared resources.

17
00:01:19,850 --> 00:01:23,363
A project directory is a small information architecture.

18
00:01:23,363 --> 00:01:26,437
Raw data should be treated as read-only.

19
00:01:26,437 --> 00:01:29,511
Workflow files describe how outputs are created.

20
00:01:29,511 --> 00:01:31,706
Scripts contain substantial analysis code.

21
00:01:31,706 --> 00:01:33,463
Environment files declare software.

22
00:01:33,463 --> 00:01:35,659
Logs and benchmarks describe execution.

23
00:01:35,659 --> 00:01:38,732
Results are generated and can be recreated.

24
00:01:38,732 --> 00:01:45,759
This separation prevents common mistakes such as editing a raw file, overwriting a result by hand,

25
00:01:45,759 --> 00:01:49,711
or losing track of which parameters produced a figure.

26
00:01:49,711 --> 00:01:56,298
Use meaningful sample identifiers and a metadata table rather than encoding all information in filenames.

27
00:01:56,298 --> 00:02:01,128
Keep secrets and patient identifiers out of Git repositories and logs.

28
00:02:01,128 --> 00:02:02,881
Scientific software has dependencies.

29
00:02:02,881 --> 00:02:10,768
One tool may need a specific Python version, another a compiled library, and a third a command-line executable.

30
00:02:10,768 --> 00:02:14,712
Installing everything globally creates conflicts and makes projects fragile.

31
00:02:14,712 --> 00:02:18,656
An environment is an isolated collection of compatible packages.

32
00:02:18,656 --> 00:02:24,353
Miniforge provides the conda and mamba tools without a large preselected package set.

33
00:02:24,353 --> 00:02:26,982
Mamba resolves and installs packages efficiently.

34
00:02:26,982 --> 00:02:30,926
Bioconda is a community channel containing many bioinformatics packages.

35
00:02:30,926 --> 00:02:35,746
An environment file records the package names and, where appropriate, versions.

36
00:02:35,746 --> 00:02:39,690
It is a recipe, not a substitute for validation.

37
00:02:39,690 --> 00:02:45,825
Part Four will explain why large active environments should not live on network storage.

38
00:02:45,825 --> 00:02:48,824
Conda is the environment and package model.

39
00:02:48,824 --> 00:02:52,252
Mamba is a compatible, faster resolver and installer.

40
00:02:52,252 --> 00:02:56,109
Miniforge is a compact distribution that provides these tools.

41
00:02:56,109 --> 00:03:00,393
Channels are package repositories, and Bioconda specializes in bioinformatics software.

42
00:03:00,393 --> 00:03:06,392
Channel order matters because packages from different repositories may be built against different libraries.

43
00:03:06,392 --> 00:03:11,963
Follow the RCC-supported configuration rather than copying arbitrary commands from an old tutorial.

44
00:03:11,963 --> 00:03:20,104
Keep the environment definition in the project, test it on synthetic data, and avoid continuously changing a shared environment

45
00:03:20,104 --> 00:03:21,818
underneath an active analysis.

46
00:03:21,818 --> 00:03:28,245
For production, a pinned container image is often more robust, as covered in Part Four.

47
00:03:28,245 --> 00:03:30,664
Snakemake is a workflow management system.

48
00:03:30,664 --> 00:03:36,307
Each rule declares input files, output files, software, resources, and a command or script.

49
00:03:36,307 --> 00:03:41,547
Snakemake builds a directed acyclic graph showing which outputs depend on which inputs.

50
00:03:41,547 --> 00:03:45,981
It runs only the steps needed to create the requested target.

51
00:03:45,981 --> 00:03:50,818
If an upstream input changes, the affected downstream steps can be recomputed.

52
00:03:50,818 --> 00:03:56,461
This is safer than a long shell script that assumes every previous command succeeded.

53
00:03:56,461 --> 00:04:00,491
The workflow graph also helps colleagues review the scientific logic.

54
00:04:00,491 --> 00:04:04,522
A dry run shows what would happen without executing commands.

55
00:04:04,522 --> 00:04:06,992
Snakemake and Slurm solve different problems.

56
00:04:06,992 --> 00:04:11,109
Snakemake understands scientific dependencies and decides which rule is ready.

57
00:04:11,109 --> 00:04:18,931
The Slurm executor translates each ready rule into a cluster job with requested CPUs, memory, runtime, and other resources.

58
00:04:18,931 --> 00:04:24,694
The lightweight Snakemake controller can run in a tmux session on the submission host.

59
00:04:24,694 --> 00:04:27,576
The expensive commands run on compute nodes.

60
00:04:27,576 --> 00:04:34,575
This separation lets a workflow execute many independent samples in parallel without manually submitting hundreds of jobs.

61
00:04:34,575 --> 00:04:40,750
Resource values should be declared per rule and refined using measurements rather than copied blindly.

62
00:04:40,750 --> 00:04:43,964
A statistical workflow starts with input validation.

63
00:04:43,964 --> 00:04:51,312
Check column names, data types, missing values, group labels, and expected sample identifiers before calculating anything.

64
00:04:51,312 --> 00:04:55,446
The demonstration dataset contains synthetic measurements from two groups.

65
00:04:55,446 --> 00:04:58,660
One rule validates and cleans the table.

66
00:04:58,660 --> 00:05:01,875
Another calculates group counts, means, and variability.

67
00:05:01,875 --> 00:05:10,601
A third performs a Welch t test and records the effect estimate and uncertainty rather than reporting only a

68
00:05:10,601 --> 00:05:11,519
p value.

69
00:05:11,519 --> 00:05:14,275
A final rule creates a figure.

70
00:05:14,275 --> 00:05:21,623
The workflow is pedagogical; the correct statistical model for a real biomedical study depends on design,

71
00:05:21,623 --> 00:05:25,756
pairing, repeated measures, batch effects, confounders, and pre-specified hypotheses.

72
00:05:25,756 --> 00:05:30,088
DNA sequence analysis introduces file formats with different purposes.

73
00:05:30,088 --> 00:05:35,383
FASTQ stores reads and quality values and is normally kept compressed.

74
00:05:35,383 --> 00:05:37,789
A reference FASTA stores sequences.

75
00:05:37,789 --> 00:05:43,084
BAM or CRAM stores aligned reads in a binary, indexable format.

76
00:05:43,084 --> 00:05:48,860
VCF stores sequence variants and may use block compression with an index.

77
00:05:48,860 --> 00:05:54,636
Quality reports summarize technical characteristics but do not automatically establish biological validity.

78
00:05:54,636 --> 00:06:02,818
A typical small workflow validates read files, performs quality control, aligns or classifies reads, creates indexed outputs,

79
00:06:02,818 --> 00:06:04,262
and summarizes results.

80
00:06:04,262 --> 00:06:11,963
Real clinical or research pipelines require validated references, contamination controls, sample identity checks, and documented versions.

81
00:06:11,963 --> 00:06:18,183
Before a substantial run, request a specific target and perform a Snakemake dry run.

82
00:06:18,183 --> 00:06:21,737
Inspect the planned rules, inputs, and job count.

83
00:06:21,737 --> 00:06:24,846
Then execute through the RCC-supported Slurm profile.

84
00:06:24,846 --> 00:06:31,510
Each rule should have a useful log, and performance-sensitive rules should have a benchmark file.

85
00:06:31,510 --> 00:06:35,508
A completed workflow is not automatically a correct workflow.

86
00:06:35,508 --> 00:06:40,395
Review exit states, expected file counts, quality metrics, and biological plausibility.

87
00:06:40,395 --> 00:06:43,948
Avoid redirecting all commands into one giant log.

88
00:06:43,948 --> 00:06:48,835
Per-rule and per-sample logs make failures diagnosable and support audit trails.

89
00:06:48,835 --> 00:06:55,234
Git records changes to text files and supports review through branches and pull requests.

90
00:06:55,234 --> 00:06:59,805
Commit the Snakefile, scripts, environment definitions, configuration templates, and documentation.

91
00:06:59,805 --> 00:07:07,119
Do not commit raw sequencing data, patient identifiers, credentials, private keys, large binary outputs, or secrets.

92
00:07:07,119 --> 00:07:12,147
Use a gitignore file to exclude generated directories and local configuration.

93
00:07:12,147 --> 00:07:17,632
Small, descriptive commits make it possible to understand how a method evolved.

94
00:07:17,632 --> 00:07:22,660
Tag or record the exact workflow version used for an analysis.

95
00:07:22,660 --> 00:07:31,345
For collaborative projects, a pull request allows a colleague to review scientific logic and operational safety before changes reach

96
00:07:31,345 --> 00:07:32,716
the main branch.

97
00:07:32,716 --> 00:07:40,072
You are ready for larger examples when the project has a clear directory structure and read-only source data;

98
00:07:40,072 --> 00:07:47,836
the software environment is declared; Snakemake can perform a dry run; the workflow submits rules through the approved Slurm

99
00:07:47,836 --> 00:07:55,191
profile; statistical inputs are validated; sequence files use appropriate compressed and indexed formats; logs and benchmarks are generated;

100
00:07:55,191 --> 00:07:59,277
and workflow changes are recorded in Git without sensitive data.

101
00:07:59,277 --> 00:08:01,729
The next lesson focuses on performance.

102
00:08:01,729 --> 00:08:09,493
It explains why an analysis with correct code can still take months when CPU, memory, and especially input-output behavior

103
00:08:09,493 --> 00:08:10,719
are structured poorly.

